2:T434,{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Article","headline":"Why Your Electric Gate is Humming But Not Moving (And How to Fix It)","description":"Is your electric gate motor humming but not moving? Discover the top reasons why and how to safely troubleshoot the issue.","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/guides/electric-gate-motor-humming-but-not-moving/","datePublished":"2026-02-21","dateModified":"2026-02-21","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/images/gates/gate-wrought-iron-ornate-daytime-manor.png","width":1200,"height":630},"author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Driveway Gates London","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Driveway Gates London","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/android-chrome-512x512.png","width":512,"height":512}},"mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/guides/electric-gate-motor-humming-but-not-moving/"}}3:T63e,{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Why is my electric gate humming but not opening?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The most common causes are a physical obstruction in the gate travel path, a blown motor start capacitor, or seized hinges. Check the full gate path for debris or obstructions first. If none are found, a failed capacitor or seized mechanism requires a professional engineer."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can I fix a humming gate motor myself?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Clearing physical obstructions is safe to do yourself after engaging the manual release. Lubricating stiff hinges with penetrating oil is also DIY-appropriate. Capacitor replacement and any electrical repair inside the motor housing should be carried out by a competent gate engineer."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How much does it cost to repair a humming gate motor in London?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"A capacitor replacement typically costs £80 to £150 including the part and labour. A new motor if the existing one has burned out costs £250 to £500 fitted. Control board replacement costs £150 to £350."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is it safe to keep using my gate if the motor hums but still moves slowly?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. A motor that is running but struggling to move the gate is under abnormal load. Continued use risks burning out the motor coil. Engage the manual release and operate the gate by hand until the fault has been diagnosed and repaired."}}]}6:["slug","electric-gate-motor-humming-but-not-moving","d"]
